After publishing videos and social media from the night of the assault to their millions of online followers, they sparked viral outrage and demands for #JusticeforJaneDoe. They unleashed a passionate mob, and their actions divided the small town, but in the process gave strength to generations of women forced to hide abuse. This film asks, when it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene [1]?” My opinion is subjective depending on details and should be looked at on a case to case basis. I generally am anti-activist; this case is slightly different in the fact that there was video evidence of wrongdoing. What these kids did was not right or moral, and they seemed aware of their actions and even laughed at the idea. They were foolish kids. Anonymous’ first video about the situation elicited a response, an emotional response before any details or evidence were shown or discussed. Generally, I do not believe that large numbers grant validity to a topic and unwavering support of justice perpetuates war in my eyes. Back in the day we thought we were doing something divine by burning witches at stake, but we were simply killing people. There are consequences to tough cases like this where it is likely to have a divide of opinions. Some will have strong ties to their beliefs and have reasons for that, and some will follow. Many opinions will be swayed for the good and for the bad. You cannot dismiss or accept any of it at face value, because you cannot predict the intent. It takes a morally sound person to be aware of the situation at hand and accept the movements that are happening as a result even if you don’t agree with them or spread the issue if you do agree with them, either action will have consequences. The free thinker might be attacked for voicing their opinion by mobs that are no better than the people committing crimes. The person who has emotional ties to the situation at hand will raise awareness, which is positive, but they might perpetuate the divide. It is hard to say what which side outweighs the other, I believe the rise in awareness and the support from others should outweigh the oppositions opinions if you are the activist. In society we tend to push a perfect opinion on people between the media, social media, etc. That is not moral. A rise in awareness is a positive notion, it is the consequences that come out of it that tend to be negative But that does not immediately make one side more right about the situation, it just means they think a different way. We should be more ready to listen than dismiss. We need to stop aligning with a cause and start discussing. Rape is undoubtedly an awful thing to do and giving women a medium to speak out on this topic is an overall positive thing. I just do not like when people with ill-intent abuse a medium or system. False accusations are a thing, and it would be foolish to dismiss that. There are plenty of cases that have been proven to be false and many that were never resolved. We live in a society that only lets one side speak out issue, and cancel the opposition, we call that “cancel culture.” Real victims like the ones in this case already have a hard time speaking up on these issues, so when a topic like this goes viral, you might not know what to believe, which throws shade on the issue you’re standing up for. Guys or even women that commit rape on another person, should be convicted. It is a morally wrong thing to do. I do not think they should be burned at a cross. They are predators and it is up to them to change that, especially in this case. The words they said were disgusting, but they were still kids, and this is exemplified by the fact that they went to juvie instead of prison. It is the mob mentality that a person’s life should be wiped off this planet that I do not agree with. I am sure after some self-thought and a sway of opinion from the town, most of the accused or convicted football players took a deep look at themselves and realized that their actions were not right. That notion may be hopeful. I believe we have an issue in this society that if someone does something, that is nearly unanimously wrong/immoral, we do not allow them to change or see the error of their ways. I may be giving too much hope to the person committing the crime, but we push perfection when that notion is unattainable. We are quick to incarcerate and ask questions later. The awareness on the subject is an overall positive outcome, and anonymous technically was morally correct in this case, although hacking is morally questionable. Overall, I do not agree with the idea of hacktivism, because it is basically using your skills to play god. They have the knowledge and power to make an issue go viral, with bots and algorithms, that are most likely breaking terms of service of most websites. Hacktivism generally aligns with a political belief which makes it biased. This case was positive for the women in the video and many others around the world, so it’s fair to overlook the notion that some may use this platform for nefarious reasons such as fame, attention, or money (status). I have two perspectives on this matter. My first take is utilitarian since more people will benefit from a rise in awareness surrounding this issue. It will give a great number of women a platform to speak out on issues that they would otherwise keep to themselves or close relatives/friends. It would also hopefully decrease the frequency in which these cases pop up. Thus, a greater number will benefit because it may affect several women around the world. My second take is more of a consequentialist approach on the matter, which is aligned with the utilitarian perspective, but since the issue was presented worldwide, it’s hard to argue the notion of greater good for greater amount of people[2]. The divide that this case caused in the town may have caused more harm than good. The close-knit community has let its ties loosen over butting heads on ideals. Many folks do not believe that rape is okay, but they would rather not stir up commotion, because they are aware of disruptions that may result. It could be exemplified if families and friends started loathing each other over such commotion. Each family being a resounding number of people overall. There is potential that issues like this are swept under the rug for a reason. It may have helped several women feel safe at the cost of a whole community. Thus, the consequence’s make it immoral. This scenario could also be switched vice versa with the last one. The question is which effect is more important. I believe there is no answer, because that would mean that we value one life (persons issues) or group over the other, and that is not exactly fair or ethical. That is why I do not generally cater to the idea of activism. If I had to pick a side, I would lean towards the rise of awareness being a greater outcome than the resulting divide. This question resembles the train conductor dilemma. Whether you value one life compared to five lives on the track as a train conductor. You need significant information to justify your answer. If five of the workers are convicted felons or murders, it tends to sway justification for one side’s answer, but the dilemma is hard to answer without details. It is still difficult for me to put value on a life regardless of such details.

There is really thin line between being good and bad in any sense. This also happens in cyber security. In cyber security, there are people called hackers. Traditionally, hackers have often been associated with crimes like theft, fraud, and vandalism. Let’s make something clear, hackers are not always bad. In fact, there exists different types of hackers. Some hackers do not have ethics. These guys will try everything to harm people, organizations, or even the system. They will try to steal credentials (usernames, passwords) and/or important documents, to rob money in transactions or, somehow, directly from the bank, and try to make organizations crash, corrupt files, information, etc. The good hackers do have ethics. These guys try to look out after people, systems, organizations, etc. They are the ones that create anti-virus programs, make sure the websites you navigate in are secure, make transactions safe and that your money cannot be stolen, make difficult for bad hackers to steal your credentials, and, of course, your systems (computers, cellphones, tablets, etc.) safe and secure. In the modern digital age, the power of hacking has been channeled into a positive good via its use as a means of protesting against unethical acts of governments and corporations. As the web has become more widely used and influential on today’s society, hacktivism is becoming a more effective way for people to fight back against the wrongdoings of larger entities and get their message out to the world. The group most widely associated with this phenomenon is Anonymous, a hacktivist network that has targeted religious cults, oppressive governments, and corporations who have crossed an ethical line set by Anonymous. I consider the actions of Anonymous to be examples of ethical hacking, as they promote public awareness of important political issues and potential human rights violations. From the perspective of the victims of Anonymous hackings, these acts may seem unethical; however, I believe that the greater good is being promoted by the hacktivism. There are many examples of Anonymous hackings that have benefitted the greater good. One of their most positive hackings was in the recent Steubenville case. In December 2012, the small town of Steubenville, Ohio was thrust into national attention when a 12-minute video depicting several of the town‘s high school football players gleefully defiling a seemingly unconscious young woman was released and posted around the internet. The persons responsible for the release of this video were members of a hacktivist collective known as Anonymous, a group who routinely uses their technological prowess as a protest technique to collect, reveal, and disseminate information which is not readily available to the public. Upon discovering that the video was created in August of the same year and that no one had yet been charged for the crimes, Anonymous began gathering and releasing any information and media that they found relevant to the case to its online audiences across multiple websites. They created a website specifically for this event where this information was also posted, which included some personal information of anyone they believed to be involved in covering up the attack, and distributed the link to the site to several social media platforms. The story and accompanying information spread rapidly across the internet, promptly reaching the news media who then began a debate regarding the ethics of the video and other information being made public. Back in Steubenville, some of its citizens believed the negative exposure brought to the town because of these alleged actions was unnecessarily tarnishing their town’s reputation. Others, however, assembled in the streets and protested the authorities’ handling of the situation outside of the county courthouse. Among the protestors at the rally were dozens of Anonymous members, as the group has found their physical presence at protests concurrent with their online hacktivist efforts to be beneficial in providing as much exposure as possible to their cause. Long story short, in a town that revolved around the high school football team, authorities attempted to cover up a sexual assault by members of the team. Deric Lostutter, a hacker from Anonymous, hacked into some systems and revealed important information that helped in proving these two guys guilty. The problem is that hacking into systems is illegal; and, though, people think Lostutter did good for society, the government charged him with 16 years of prison. And, finally, although the government’s charge was eventually dropped against Deric Lostutter, he still received a two-year prison sentence for his participation in an Anonymous operation undertaken in solidarity with a rape victim in Steubenville, Ohio. According to Lostutter’s lawyer, his sentence was “a year more than one of the rapists got”. The Steubenville High School Rape that occurred in 2012 launched hacker groups further into popularity, gaining them notoriety and praise. In the December following the sexual assault, Anonymous took justice into their own hands by threatening the people of Steubenville and taking direct action. Anonymous leaked information about 50,000 residents that they believed were the perpetrators and conspirators, threatening the town with further action if justice was not achieved; this signaled the start of #occupySteubenville. Anonymous became a powerful ally to the 16-year-old victim, organizing a protest, posting videos of the alleged assaulters laughing at their acts, and leaking court transcripts. Members of Anonymous were catalysts in bringing the case to national attention by releasing private emails and videos of the criminals and obstructers. The newfound national attention brought to light the debate over rape culture, which is an important discussion and educational moment for today’s society. The private documents were also used as evidence in court to eventually convict the criminals involved. Thus, with this revelation through hacktivism, the wrongdoers have been punished and the spread of illegal material has been halted. By stopping unethical behavior in this case and many others, Anonymous has demonstrated that their hacks promote the greater good and thus, are ethical. The opposing view is that Anonymous has been unethical. Followers of deontological ethics will argue that hacktivism is unethical, as it involves an intrusion of private information, analogous to a real life “break and enter”. In the process of hacktivism, information on the web may be stolen, defaced, or destroyed. Clearly, these actions are against the law and cause harm to the owners of a website. Anonymous also breaks the hacker ethical code which states that hacking is “ethically OK as long as the cracker commits no theft, vandalism, or breach of confidentiality.” However, I will argue that the ends justify the means in this case. Hacktivism by Anonymous is a form of protest that raises public awareness of important issues, which is a positive good. As mentioned above, Anonymous leaks have also been integral in capturing criminals, making their actions even more valuable to society as a whole. Also, by showing corporations and governments that evil will not be tolerated, hacktivism by Anonymous acts as a deterrent for future corruption. Though the means are unlawful, the end result benefits the greater good, making the actions ethical by the utilitarian view. Also, I believe that the intentions of Anonymous are virtuous, as they primarily target their hackings towards those who have done wrong in their eyes. Opposing those who commit evil is a valiant act in the name of good, so hacktivism is ethical when we consider the character of Anonymous. In conclusion, I would consider the actions of Anonymous to be ethical as they result in a positive good for society and they are virtuous in character.

What is the role of Anonymous, a hacker organization, in the rape case of teenagers in the small town of Steubenville? This question always lingers in my mind when I watch the movie of Anonymous Comes to Town by Nancy Schwartzman and Steven Lake. On the one hand, from the local point of view, Anonymous is undoubtedly persecuting the victims and the reputation of the local proud high school football team. On the other hand, from the perspective of all rape victims across the United States, Anonymous is a pioneer in leading oppressed women against the current unfair situation. Perhaps under the cold treatment of the local police, if there is no Anonymous’ intervention, things may not have subsequent changes. However, some of the rumors that followed did bring shame to the town. Essentially, this situation is a balance between ethics and people’s privacy. Objectively speaking, in this rape case, the Anonymous’ action is attractive enough to change the American's cognition and attitude towards rape. As many local women express in the film: if there is no Anonymous’ intervention, they will have to swallow their anger and defend by themselves, because it is difficult to seek help from the local police and judges. It can be said that the Anonymous successfully introduced the rape case in a humble place into the eyes of the American public, making it a hot topic at that time. This has undeniably promoted the progress of relevant laws in the United States, which is remarkable. Obviously, anonymous uploads initiated by the hacker group Anonymous successfully aroused the attention of the people of the whole country to rape. As time went on, rumors outside the town became more and more uncontrollable, so that protestors from all over the country gathered in the town to vent their anger at criminals and their dissatisfaction with the law. The oppressed women spontaneously put on the mask of Anonymous to tell their own experiences and the injustice of the law. It is the Anonymous who gives them courage and inspiration to face their past humiliation. From the moment they put on the mask of Anonymous, the painful experience is no longer their shame and burden, on the contrary, it has become a powerful weapon for them to protect their legitimate rights and interests. It also helps these victims recover their mental health to a certain extent, like what Michele Robinson states at the end of the film: "it just made me feel like a brand-new person. It is like I was set free for some reason." However, from a moral point of view, it is a great disrespect for the privacy of others to record and upload the process of assault without the permission of the people concerned. Consequential, these social media records spread the information about the rape quickly to news organizations all over the country, making the case continue to ferment, and eventually lead to the serious damage to the reputation of the town and enduring impact on the residents' lives. As described in the film, many people in this town of Steubenville still affected by the rape case, which already had happened eight years ago. What is worse, some of the residents were even labeled "monsters" by the outside community since the inaction of the local police. The reality under the camera is cruel. Most of the residents in the small town did not want to see any related content on social media. Instead, they hoped to bury these painful memories in the deepest of the heart, letting time wash and heal the damaged soul, so as to start a new life sooner. However, these yearning for a better life, in the eyes of the outside community, has become a concrete manifestation of their local “rape culture”. From this perspective, the impact of Anonymous brought to the town has become a disaster to some extent. In addition, posting the extremely sensitive topic of rape on social media without the permission of the victim, would have an immeasurable impact on the victim herself. In this case, the Anonymous were considered irresponsible to the victims since they were hardly prepared to take corresponding risks before releasing relevant assault videos. Considering the progress of the events that have taken place, the victim is safe and sound, but this only proves that her psychological quality is good. However, considering the possible situation that could occur in a similar case, that is, the farce ends with the victim's suicide, I am afraid that the public opinion will eventually turn to the verbal attack on the Anonymous that is against the original intention of their action, which may cause the consequence of destruction to both sides. Fortunately, the development of the situation was not as bad as expected. It eventually evolved into a women's rights movement. Looking at the action of the Anonymous in this case objectively, they have made outstanding contributions to the oppressed women in the United States. The Anonymous exposed the ethical problems hidden behind rape with the most authentic assault video, which made people dare to fight back and seek justice. Besides, it has a profound impact on the daily life of the town residents. Sadly, the difference in the way dealing the rape case made them the target of social media criticism. More importantly, the impact it has on the victim in this rape case is complex, there are both the dark side and the good side. After all, compared with the conservative treatment of rape cases by the local police and judges, Anonymity is the one who really made a difference. In fact, such scandals revealed by hackers would more or less cause social panic. This is undoubtedly a public declaration of war on personal privacy since Anonymous can expose people's private life to public community at any time. However, in terms of the social conditions of the United States at that time, the long-standing public anger over rape cases has made this social panic negligible. Besides, social media played a very important role that cannot be ignored in the whole process when Anonymous advocates the pursuit of freedom and the protection of individual rights. In fact, the Anonymous has been exploring the bottom line of morality and law from all the time. Among their actions, social media has become an indispensable part of all participants in its activities, because all information that Anonymous want to spread, whether legal or illegal, can be quickly and effectively disseminated through it. What is more, It seems like this social media feature also minimizes the guilt of Anonymous. Combined with the above points, it can be said that the role of Anonymous in this case is more like a pioneer of the rights movement than a hacker who ignores others' privacy. Even though the methods adopted by Anonymous in publicizing the assault video was not appropriate to the victim, it turned out that they have undeniably protected the legitimate interests of the majority of people on the macro level. This fact made it difficult to weigh the Anonymous’ action in the case, since the Anonymous did inevitably violate the privacy of the victim while protecting the public rights interests. From a radical point of view, a series of actions of Anonymous have strengthened the state's attention to rape cases, which is a symbol of the progress of the times; from a moral point of view, although these measures have sacrificed the legitimate rights and interests of the individual, they have finally achieved the unanimous criticism of relevant cases across the country. In one word, with all these comprehensive analyses, the ethical role of anonymity in this case is more likely to be the representative of justice than just the divulger of privacy.

In August 2012, two football players from small town Steubenville, Ohio were accused of raping a 16 year-old Jane Doe. Local law enforcement did not do the best job of digging up evidence for the case as complaints from residents regarding the case seemed to be swept under the rug. This resulted in various rallies, the popular social media hashtag #JusticeforJaneDoe, and a very divided Steubenville. This is when hacker group, Anonymous, and specific members like Deric Lostutter intervened to expose significant information to prove that the football players had in fact raped the 16 year-old. Justice was served, but arguably at inconsistent degrees among all the various suspects. The two football players were found guilty of raping Jane Doe the night of August 11, 2012 and were sentenced to one and two years in juvenile detention. As for Losutter, the one who exposed the football players for their crime, he was set to face up to 25 years in prison for the illegal actions of what he did to expose the case. In 2016, he was ultimately sentenced to two years in federal prison for “[hacking] a website associated with Steubenville High School athletics and to a second charge of lying to an FBI agent who was investigating the breach.” This rape case and how the evidence got exposed explores how we view whistleblowers in society and whether the current laws that we have in place for internet rights/hacktivism are up to date and actually reflect how just our government truly is. The Steubenville, Ohio case regarding a 16 year-old girl being raped by two football players and how internet hackers exposed the case brings cybercrime severity, hacktivism, and the definition of just society into question. From recent news about countries like China and Russia infiltrating the United States’ attempts at security, it is safe to say that hacking, whether on a national, international, or town-wide scale, is becoming more and more normalized. Why governments hack one another remains unclear, but there has been an uptick in government hacking. The more normalized an aspect becomes, the more people will feel as though it is socially acceptable to do, which is probably part of the reason why Losutter felt the need to expose the football players by any means necessary. The line between being just and being ethical becomes very blurry when evaluating crime within a governed society. Ethical guidelines like positive rights, negative rights, and the freedom paradox ensure that citizens may act freely without having to worry about their government infringing too much on their lives to the point where they no longer feel free. An action may be the right thing to do, but within a community, may be painted as morally wrong. In the case of the Steubenville High School football players who were exposed by hacker group, Anonymous, I do believe that the hackers were serving justice whilst exposing these videos of the two football players explicitly saying and showing that Jane Doe had been raped. Of course the methodology they used to expose these videos and put them on the internet to gain awareness was unethical in terms of the school’s and the football players’ privacy, but there are only so many way to get people to listen and get justice for a rape victim, explaining how though justice and ethics go hand in hand, but cannot be meshed together without considering the circumstances of the situation. One specific example that stood out to me in this case was hacker, Noah McHugh, and the compromising of Steubenville High School’s booster club website. McHugh had hacked into the website and reposted Lostutter’s video where he is masked and threatening everyone involved in the rape case to come forward or risk getting all their personal information shared. McHugh revealed that it was not at all difficult to obtain access to their website. He also tweeted that “[It was] not a government site or anything,” and so “It would be the same as [him] hacking into a WordPress. Not much the cops do about it.” This is where I think it is important to discuss severity of the cybercrime. I feel as though most, if not all, cybercrime consequences are very intense compared to other crimes. I theorize that this is because of how new the cyber and tech is to everyone. This also explains why authorities struggle with coming up with consequences for crimes involving tech. The current laws we have in place are not tailored to incorporate cyber crime and perhaps this is why hackers get the short end of the stick even if they are doing something for the greater good, proving why severity of the cybercrime plays such a crucial role in coming up with consequences for hacking. Take the Computer Fraud and Abusive Act as an example. This is the main antihacking law that Congress passed in the 1980s. The CFAA’s original purpose was to make sure that businesses were not doing anything unauthorized. It really only covers computer crimes, but we now know that this is outdated since one can hack social media from mobile devices: two aspects that had not yet existed when the CFAA was but in place. The CFAA “predates social networks, smartphones, and sophisticated information gathering.” and so I believe it would be wise for the United States government to review various antihacking laws every so often so that local authorities, much like Steubenville, are not at a loss when they are presented with a case where hackers are doing something for the greater good and getting justice for a victim of rape. To elaborate on government’s role in regulating hacktivism and whether or not the people who carry it out should be penalized, I think it is extremely important for there to be a Good Samaritan Law equivalent for cyber-related crimes. I do not agree with what the Steubenville authorities charged the football players and hacktivists with. The length of their sentences should have been switched. The football players were the ones who committed the worse of the two crimes and all the hackers did was expose it illegally. It is unfortunate that they were not able to expose the video of the football players admitting to raping Jane Doe in a legal manner, but no one can deny that the video and various other pictures that surfaced did not help the case. There is a reason why, for example, if a police officer is responding to a 911 call about an abuser and comes to search the house and sees drugs on the table in the house, they may not drop everything and arrest the people in the house for possession of drugs. This reason is because “Good Samaritan laws are written to encourage bystanders to get involved in these and other emergency situations” without having to worry about being the ones to blame. Were it not for the hackers, no justice would be served and a lot of local, corrupt authorities in Steubenville would have not resigned had their integrity been questioned. The act of hacking may not have been the most ethical choice, but if justice is served as a result, the morality of the illegally hacking and uncovering crucial evidence should nullify one another.

Vigilante justice has been a topic of discussion for centuries. From stories of retribution in the bible and Greek myth to Anonymous carrying out their own vendetta, there has been a long and rich history of people taking matters into their own hands outside the purview of the law. The reason it pervades may be because there is a lack of confidence in legal systems that fail citizens often miserably, where the only other option seems to be to put up with the injustice or shut up. This seems to be the issue in the case of the horrifying and disgusting assault of a teen girl by two football players in Steubenville, Ohio. Knowledge of the incident was widespread among the student populace due to explicit pictures and tweets about the incident being circulated, as well as an accompanying video where a male student remarks on “how hard she was raped”[1]. It seemed the town cared more about their squeaky-clean image than about pursuing charges for this teen girl’s horrific nightmare assault. This was until hacker group Anonymous decided to intervene, simultaneously bringing worldwide attention to a contentious issue, and causing the town of Steubenville to be under constant scrutiny from worldwide entities. How might we view this event and surrounding vigilantism from an ethical perspective? There are different ideas around the ethics of vigilantism. We can view the events that transpired under the ethical system of utilitarianism. Without measuring any other attributes of the town and the young girl, these two groups start off as equal in utility. If you view the town as a collection of many members instead of a single entity, the town has far more inherent utility due to negative consequences to the town being amplified by thousands of community members[3]. An indictment of their beloved football team would be stressful for school officials, parents, cops, and other students, causing overwhelmingly negative outcomes. Furthermore, in this way, Anonymous remains far away from the conflict. A member of Anonymous is not personally affected when they launch an attack on the town. In the documentary on this issue, the townspeople are angry, dejected, and indignant over what they view as undeserving attacks on their character[1]. Perhaps they do not deserve such treatment from a utilitarian perspective, where the utility of the town far exceeds the utility of the young girl. However, if you instead view the town as a singular entity and the young girl as another entity of equal inherent value, it becomes very clear that the indignance of the town is not an appropriate reason to brush a violent sexual assault under the rug. I would argue that the negative experience of the girl is so intense and so damaging that it is ethical to pursue vigilante justice. Rawls’ ideas of fairness support my idea. He places a high utility on disadvantaged groups and a far lower utility on those who are already in positions of power [3]. As an entity, the town has far more power than this one girl, and as such, she is in a disadvantaged position. This is further shown when members of the town, as well as teachers at the school, call her a liar and are supported by other town members [2]. Rawls says that we should decide our actions based on the most vulnerable members of society [3]. He furthermore states that reasonable laws will be obeyed by reasonable people. If the outcome of this event – a horrific and well documented rape being ignored by the town – was reasonable, thousands of members of Anonymous would not have challenged it. Is it not ethical, then, to pursue vigilantism? Although more community members feel more negative than positive about their lives being uprooted by Anonymous, the women that are encouraged to speak and heal from their own assaults also have greater value than the town under Rawls’ social theories [1]. Vigilantism that targets the disadvantaged or is an act of self-individuation instead of helping others is also unethical under this theory. However, it is clear that in the case of Steubenville, Ohio, there is reason to believe that Anonymous’ actions were justified and ethical. Furthermore, we have not analyzed the difference this makes on a viral scale: when vigilante justice goes viral online, there is a measurable interest in these cases that often show people the hope for their own situations on a global scale. It also shows people that you cannot get away with sexually assaulting women, as the value of these women as disadvantaged members of society succeeds a rapist’s value. From this perspective, utilitarianism supports vigilantism as the positive worldwide outcome far exceeds the town’s negative outcome. This is shown increasingly more, as our ideas around justice for sexual assault survivors have developed in recent years. Was Ronan Farrow writing an investigation on Harvey Weinstein a form of legal vigilante justice? He was not backed by the law, he was attacking Weinstein’s character, and his evidence was largely anecdotal in nature. We would argue no, due to the intrinsic importance of shining a spotlight on evil behavior. If the same logic is applied to this case, this form of vigilante justice enhances, not erodes, our society. Utilitarianism does have flaws, as it has no reasonable framework for what is “moral,” only what is of utility based on outcomes [4]. Perhaps when this case is viewed as an isolated incident with Anonymous perpetrating against an innocent town, utilitarianism can be applied to support the town over the vigilantes. However, there are interpretations of this event that when utilitarianism is applied, does support Anonymous, as their actions may have helped the outcomes of millions of people’s lives in a small way. Additionally, when viewed through the lens of Rawls, vigilantism by Anonymous is justified. Society is only as strong as its most vulnerable members under his theories [3]. Anonymous was justified in improving society by making decisions on behalf of the disadvantaged to benefit mankind as a whole, rather than just the town. When considering acts of vigilante justice, one should ask themselves if it will benefit mankind and if it will help the least advantaged people in our society.

In 2012, Steubenville High School’s football team players gang-raped an unconscious teenage girl. Anonymous hacker exposed the Steubenville High School rape case to the public to bring the case to national attention. He achieved to incite an intense public outcry against many in the town who seemed to neglect and blame the victim rather than the rapists Consequently, the so-called “hacktivity” enabled and encouraged women who had been forced to hide their experience of sexual assault to speak out [2]. It seems the hacker was a hero and brought justice to the surface. However, the hacker was not able to avoid liability for his action because he violated several laws. What is good and bad does not always correspond to what is legal or illegal. But both cases are really depending on a very slight line between justice and overreach. At least, we know his action was a crime since he was arrested. But we should think carefully in order to decide a position on whether he was good or bad. We will approach it by analyzing the ethical aspects of his action. Before we jump into the analysis of ethical aspects, it is essential to understand some relatively important terminologies. First of all, “hacking” refers to the intentional and unauthorized access to computer systems [3]. We call the Anonymous hacker a “hacktivist” who performs an act of hacktivism. “Hacktivism” is the use of hacking as a form of civil disobedience, for a politically or socially, but not profitably, motivating purpose. As a hacktivist is a computing professionals, I will analyze the ethical aspects applicable to the case based on the ACM Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct and by applying deontological ethics. Hacking itself cannot be considered ethical. According to the ACM Code of Ethics, it is considered ethical when computing professionals access computing and communication resources only if authorized [7]. However, the hacker gained the access to the website without permission. Hacking on social media, as intellectual property, is an act of infringing not only on legal rights but ethical rights as well[6]. In addition, according to philosopher Immanuel Kant’s system of ethics, we can argue that his action was not ethical because hacking could not be made into a categorical imperative [6]. Every people cannot constantly be hacking each other, “regardless of the cause, because then there would be cyber unrest within the Internet [6].” He was using the people and their property “as a means to an end,” social justice, instead of allowing people to be treated “as a mean in themselves.[6]” Therefore, it would be unethical to take over the website. Hacktivist’s action was not ethical because he violated the privacy of others. Privacy threats include intentional and institutional uses of personal information, unauthorized use or release, theft of information, and leakage of information. It is not ethically acceptable according to the ACM Code of Ethics. It states, “computing professionals should only use personal information for legitimate ends and without violating the rights of individuals and groups [7].” But he intimidated and violated privacy in several ways. First, he hacked a fan website Roll Red Roll dedicated to the football team. Breaking into a target’s system without permission is a kind of trespass. It does not matter if it was done with good intentions because it obviously violates the privacy of anyone involved in/to the website. Moreover, he leaked its owner’s personal emails online [1]. Also, he threatened to reveal personal identifying information of those students involved in the incident unless they came out to the public to apologize to the victim [2]. He even threatened to expose the names of various school and law enforcement officials who the hacker believed had covered up the case [4]. Lastly, he exposed the perpetrators’ personal information including names and faces. He hacked and leaked the video taken and shared on the day of the incident by the crime’s perpetrators. A perpetrator’s face was clearly captured in the video with his joke about the sexual assault. It was the key action that shed more light on what might be happened to the victim and caught enthusiastic national attention. It really worked but it was ethically wrong because it violated the perpetrator’s privacy. A criminal is still a human and has a human right. It cannot be justified to violate his privacy for any reason even though he seemed to deserve it. Violating one’s privacy is related to causing harm to the person. The ACM Code of Ethics suggests professionals avoid harm. It defines what “harm” means; “negative consequences, especially when those consequences are significant and unjust,” which includes unjustified disclosure of information. The disclosure of the perpetrators’ personal information was unjust because it was not his role to punish them. We need to remember that there is no actually harmless hacking [3]. The film throws a question: “When is it okay for outsiders to intervene when it seems like nothing will change?” For the question, I feel that when to intervene would be considered okay for outsiders is not the main concern. The way and the method they apply to intervene should be the most important factor to check. The hacker said his hacking on the website was done with just an intention to expose information about the gang rape. He said [1], “We wanted to stand up for a girl who had no voice, and we went about it the wrong way.” The point is the way the action is taken. Many people think hacktivism is effective and necessary as a modern form of protest, which is a vital aspect of the development of our society. The research studied that more than half of people believe hacktivist groups are required to step in when no one else will [5]. The victim had no voice and nobody in the town seemed to speak out about the rape case. I would support hacktivists to intervene if they just encourage the audience to have a harmless protest. However, we should know that it is not their role to judge, expose, and punish. They have to be careful about how and how much they intervene. Then, their action will possibly be considered ethical even if they will still take charge of crime. To sum up, I see certain ethical responsibilities the Anonymous hacker who exposed the Steubenville High School rape case holds. His “hactivity” cannot be considered ethical even if the purpose and the consequence of the action looked good and nice because he did not respect the privacy of others and his action was reasonably considered as harmful for others since he hacked.

On the night of August 11, 2012, an intoxicated, underage high-school girl was publicly sexually assaulted by members of the school football team. The proof of this event was undeniable, as many of the students who participated in this horrible act even documented what they did on video. Included in this evidence is a video where a group of underage boys are laughing about the rape, and making comments like “they raped her quicker than Mike Tyson raped that one girl.” The boy who made that comment, Michael Nodianos, was not even directly involved in the rape, but received countless death threats, both to himself and his entire family, and ended up dropping out of school. While it is blatantly obvious that rape is horrible and wrong, the film “Anonymous Comes to Town” asks the interesting question, “when it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene?” It seems as though this should have an obvious answer. However, if the situation is analyzed from both points of view, an ethical argument can be made for either side, even if it may require playing devil’s advocate. This essay will first present the positive arguments for Anonymous’ intervention from the perspective of Utilitarianism, and then present an argument from the standpoint of Deontology as to why it may have been bad. While it is true that the intervention from Anonymous had a few questionable side effects, when viewed through the lens of Utilitarianism, it is obvious that their actions were justified. As a quick recap, “Utilitarianism” defines actions as being right if they are for the benefit of a majority. The hacking by Anonymous shed international light onto the potential size of the rape culture in the world, and provided countless women with the courage to support one another and stand up for what is right, and to seek justice for the crimes committed against them. In the video “Anonymous Comes to Town,” it is even stated that the movement could be equated to how coal miners or factory workers go on strike together when their jobs are threatened. It is almost definitely true that without Anonymous’ involvement, this story would not have gained national attention, and justice would not have been carried out. When interviewed about his motivations, the Anonymous agent involved stated “I was always raised to stick up for people who are getting bullied” [1]. A piece of evidence to support this could be a statement from Bill Johnson of Ohio’s 6th congressional district, who declared that “As the father of two daughters and grandfather of four granddaughters, had something like what is being alleged here have happened to one of my loved ones, I would be demanding justice to the fullest extent of the law” in January of 2013, only after Anonymous started the viral controversy [3]. While the intervention from Anonymous did give courage to countless women to stand together and support one another and get justice for the victim, it did also have a several notable negative effects. According to the Stanford Encyclopedia of Psychology, “Deontology” holds that “some choices cannot be justified by their effects—that no matter how morally good their consequences, some choices are morally forbidden.” The way that Anonymous went about bringing this story to the world is highly controversial. Firstly, they hacked the high school’s website, which is extremely illegal. Additionally, they leaked the video mentioned previously, where the students were laughing about the rape. This video destroyed the future of the student Michael Nodianos, who was not even directly involved in the crime. Anonymous were complete outsiders, and they violated the privacy of these people and had a negative impact on them that will shape the remainder of their lives. Is it truly fair for Michael Nodianos to have to drop out of school and receive threats for a crime that he didn’t commit? While the jokes that he made were horrible, is it truly ethical to ruin a minor’s future because of a few minutes of tasteless joking? Furthermore, the case destroyed the reputation of the entire area. The internet branded Steubenville as a “rape town” and threw blanket insults at the entire town population, most of whom were completely uninvolved in the crime that was committed. It also had a lasting effect on the culture of the town itself. The football team “Beg Red” was at the center of this small-town community. According to a local, “Everybody around here goes to games on Friday nights, and I mean everybody — people come for miles. It's basically the small-town effect. People live and die based on Big Red because they usually win, and it makes everybody feel good about themselves when times are tough” [2]. This sense of town comfort has now been disrupted, all thanks to Anonymous’ intervention. As noble as Anonymous’ intentions may have been, they still seriously violated the law. It should be noted that this is not inherent in the declaration of a choice’s ethicality, but it still should be stated. The Anonymous agent who carried out the acts, eventually found out to be a man named Deric Lostutter, had his house raided by the FBI for his involvement in the Steubenville rape case. When raiding his house, the government “carted off his computers and Xbox” [1]. When viewing this case through the lens of Utilitarianism, it seems obvious that Anonymous’ intervention was ethical and justified. It got justice for the victim, and started a movement dedicated to ending rape culture. This movement has helped countless women, inspiring unity and support. However, when viewed through the lens of Deontology, things are not quite as clear. The way that Anonymous carried out their intervention were certainly not ethical. They illegally hacked a school’s website. They stole personal information and posted it for everyone to see, seriously violating their privacy. They ruined the future of a young boy, who just said a few tasteless jokes, and was otherwise completely uninvolved in the crime. As is the case with most ethical issues, there is no correct answer here. Whether of not Anonymous’ intervention was undeniably ethical simply depends on whatever ethical lens you use to analyze it. Regardless, I still support the government’s decision to punish the Anonymous agent who carried out the deed, because, regardless of its ethicality, no single person or organization one should be able to be judge, jury, and executioner on events like this. It is far too much power in the hands of the internet. For even if this event was ethical, who’s to say that the next one will be?

Abstract Media and technology affect society in many ways. In the Jane Doe case media and social outsiders play an important role in the outcome of the case. There will be an emphasis throughout the essay on how social outsiders had a role throughout the case and how this affected those involved. This example will help show how this resulted in different outcomes and how ethical implications affected everyone. Janiece Mary Padilla As the field of technology grows, there is an increase in the presence of technology in individuals’ daily lives. With the usage of social media as a communication tool, ethical standards have been developed and norms have been implicitly placed. In addition, the widespread utilization of networking sites has presented people with an opportunity to be social outsiders and even vigilantes for important matters. This creates a dynamic situation where social outsiders intervene in matters that generally do not involve them resulting in questioning whether this behavior is ethical. It is important to note that the analyzation of the ethics of the actions can change depending on factors such as perspective, nature of the matter and location. In a controversial case known as #JusticeforJaneDoe the hacker group “Anonymous” released videos that led to major changes in a small town. This case will be examined to show how media and social outsiders can dynamically change how society reacts to controversial topics when presented through these mediums. The two points to be discussed are how “Anonymous” motivated individuals to act and how the people involved where affected by their actions. These points will help analyze when should social outsiders use media to intervene in controversial topics. The case presented above provided an overview of the importance of media and its effects when information is distributed online.[1] In the controversial video released by “Anonymous” a man was shown mocking the young woman that was sexually assaulted after the incident had taken place. This resulted in wave of controversy that changed the course of the case. However, this action alone presents ethical questions for the group that released this video clip. In the situation presented the man involved had privacy rights that were disregarded by the anonymous group and media. Through this action the man’s identity became exposed and was put in the public eye and shared across through various media networks.[2] According to the authors of “A gift of fire: social, legal, and ethical issues for computing technology” there are three aspects of privacy including “freedom of intrusion, control of information about oneself, and freedom from surveillance.” By the anonymous group releasing the video of the man they placed him in a situation where his life could have been in jeopardy. Although people would argue that his behavior was wrong by his identity being exposed his privacy was being intruded and he was not able to control information about him like his appearance. If something had occurred to the man in the video then the victim would have been left without justice therefore in this case it can be seen as ethically wrong for the outsiders to have released the information in that manner. The Anonymous group changed how people saw media and what it could do for them in their lives. The Jane Doe case was revolutionary in many ways for the town and for the rest of the world. It changed the way the town was seen in the public eye, people who were not involved were overshadowed by the infamy of this case. In addition, people viewed authorities in a different manner after the incident. The “vigilante” group presented another ethical implication that affected the community by taking this sort of action. The group presented the information in a manner that broke through barriers in the specific community involved. Anonymous did not seek permission from anyone to post the videos to various platforms. As a result, the controversy led to rallies and a national limelight on this case. Many individuals from the town saw the actions made by the group as unethical due to negative image related to the area. In this way it was unethical because it brought negative attention to town as a whole and overshadowed the good in the town. This situation showed that people care about how they are viewed and the effects of one incident can impact the image of everyone involved. If the case was brought up in the same manner by news outlets, then the outcome would have been different as communication “norms” would have been followed. The vigilante group showed that social outsiders do influence society and that media when used in different ways can be a powerful tool. In this case Anonymous did a good job in bringing a situation that would have been forgotten into the spotlight. Some people might say that the groups behavior was ethical because the actions taken resulted in national attention and would have not if done otherwise. The results were the most important results from this case as women around the country would gain motivation to speak about their own experiences. Although this case presented some ethical implications, we can see that social outsider can help others in society who might not be able to get the resources or information they need. Media and technology helped set the path for people to pay attention to matters that occur in their communities and be able to take action and speak out. This shows how essential it is to have these tools in our daily lives. In the future there is hope that there is a way where a group like “Anonymous” can provide information and advice to others in a positive manner and create similar results. It is always up to each individual to take action when they see information on media, and this is something that can vary and change depending on factors like personal experience, location and beliefs. Media and technology presented people with a tool that allows people to take a stand and be able to get justice at the right times.

Hacktivism, a combination of hacking and activism, means precisely what it sounds like. Righteous hackers on the internet, fueled by a specific cause, use their programming skills to cause a general public uproar and raise awareness for situations they feel are not getting enough attention. Anonymous, one such hacker group, put their skills to use in 2013 to bring attention to a rape case that they felt was not receiving the care and attention it deserved. They compromised websites, stole personal data, and essentially blackmailed several officials in the name of getting justice for the rape victim. While many lauded them as heroes and champions of justice, others would just as soon see these self-proclaimed activists in a cell. Is hacktivism ethical? Is it justified to commit these objectively unethical acts if the ultimate purpose is to bring justice to criminals who performed a heinous deed? The most exciting thing happening in the town of Steubenville, Ohio is usually the local football game, which is arguably the town’s most popular pastime. In the summer of 2013, however, things took a dark turn when members of the football team recorded themselves raping a 16-year-old girl at a party. While the town law enforcement was investigating and ultimately prosecuting the incident independently, the story caught the attention of the New York Times, which then turned the eyes of the entire nation to look upon this small Ohio town in horror. Within the town, these accusations towards members of the football team were not what one would call new, and definitely not unheard of. The culture in Steubenville, however, had become one that shielded the perpetrators at the expense of the victims. The rape in 2013 may have been the proverbial straw that broke the camel’s back, then. Some on the internet, members of the hacktivist group Anonymous, felt like taking justice into their own hands since they believed that the investigation being conducted was not doing enough to ensure justice for the victims. The local school website was compromised by the group, and they gained access to it, supposedly by simply guessing the password, which ended up being the name of the football team. Additionally, the group posted videos of the actual rape from the night in question, where the rapists are laughing and casually talking about the fact that they are actively violating a human being. The release of the videos sparked even more outrage in an already tense situation. These acts drew massive attention to the Steubenville, leading to protests in the normally quiet town. Many gathered outside the Jefferson County Courthouse, most wearing Guy Fawkes masks as a symbol of Anonymous, chanting and demanding justice for not only the most recent victim of sexual violence by the Steubenville football team, but for every person that has had this happen to them but were unable to speak out or seek aid. For some in the town, they felt Anonymous’ presence and spotlight was a good thing in the fight for justice. Others, namely administrators and teachers from the school the perpetrators belong to, claimed that Anonymous’ presence and actions were not only illegal, but stood on no moral grounds, and that they were simply seeking infamy. Considering that faculty from the school, along with the actual perpetrators of the rape, were convicted on grounds relating to the rape investigation, it is my opinion that these administrators and teachers were simply trying to cover their bases and limit liability to themselves. However, the question being posed by them is inherently valid. Why is it okay for people on the internet to take things into their own hands whenever they feel like dishing out vigilante justice? In a perfect world, this would not even be a question. Of course you can’t hack into websites and databases, obtain personal information, and blackmail people into resigning, because in a perfect world, the law enforcement agency responsible for the apprehension of criminals would do the job perfectly and wrap it up with a bow on top. However, this is obviously not the case. I believe that in drastic situations such as the one in Steubenville, where there was such an obvious failing of the establishment, either due to corruption or negligence, extra-governmental bodies should get involved in one way or another. In the 21st century, a phone can make a world of difference. In fact, the idea that one can make a positive difference through use of computers is the entire basis of hacktivism. While Anonymous’ activities, specifically in Steubenville, are a gross violation of several people’s right to privacy, it’s my opinion that if the people who are having their information stolen are also actively trying to impede an investigation into the rape of a 16 year old girl, solely to protect the reputation of the town, school, and football team, then these people have put themselves at odds with basic human decency. Ultimately, I believe that if a community’s institutions (schools, law enforcement, etc.) are unable or unwilling to protect victims by bringing perpetrators to justice, then maybe third parties should begin to get involved and right the wrongs that have undeniably been committed, in an explicitly non-violent way. Admittedly, “basic human decency” is not a very measurable metric, and might vary from person to person, so I’d like to put my opinions aside and discuss the other side of the hacktivism argument. Hacktivism may be outright unethical in any situation, because in most cases, it involves illegal compromise of private data, blackmailing, as well as publicly exposing the illicitly acquired private data. Even for the worst of the worst of humanity, some might feel that these people still deserve their basic right to privacy, especially since there is no governing body within hacktivist groups like Anonymous, who are still just human beings, capable of making mistakes. One such mistake comes into play, once again, in the Steubenville case. As mentioned before, the local school’s website was compromised, and private information stolen. One administrator, Jim Parks, was accused by Anonymous of being a pedophile for having pictures of young girls in his email, and then began to concoct a theory about how administrators at the school might be paying football players to rape young girls and record it. This however, proved to be unfounded, and the girls on Parks’ email were actually of age. One can see how damaging hacktivism can be, especially if the good intentioned, self-righteous hackers accidentally land an innocent person in their crosshairs. To conclude, hacktivism is definitely a slippery slope when it comes to the ethics surrounding it. On one hand, hacktivism, and hacktivist activities from groups like Anonymous raise awareness in situations where there would otherwise be none. People who would never have a voice suddenly find themselves speaking to a nation, which is an immensely powerful thing. However, we must also consider the unintended and messy side effects of hacktivism, specifically when innocent people are accidentally targeted, like in the case of Jim Parks. There will not be a blanket answer for all hacktivism, since each situation will obviously vary, I feel confident in saying that Anonymous’ actions in Steubenville, Ohio, were justified, and brought much needed attention onto a town that had fallen into a culture of sweeping horrific acts under the rug.

The Steubenville sexual assault case that Anonymous brought to the forefront in late 2012 is fairly well known across the US and has consequences that continue to echo today, potentially being an example of the early stages of the #MeToo movement. Hearing similar stories of girls being sexually assaulted or other crimes being committed and covered up in a small town is not a super rare occurrence, so this raises the question that The Guardian’s documentary asks, “when it seems like nothing will change, when is it OK for outsiders to intervene?”. [1] I do not think anyone would disagree that the sexual assault would be morally or ethically wrong, but what about the consequences of bringing huge attention to the town to try and bring a sort of mob justice to get it solved like Anonymous did? The people behind Anonymous in this instance made the ethically right decision by using the name and media to bring attention to this case in both Utilitarian and Deontological Ethics. To start things off, let us first review what Anonymous is and does. Anonymous is not a physical group really, more of an idea that people can get behind; there is no membership roster or anything like that, just a loose association of people with a common goal or interest. Anonymous generally consists of hacktivism, or activism via hacking, but not necessarily limited to it. They operate digitally most often and bring attention to what they deem as injustice or wrong, such as bringing attention to the Steubenville rape or in the past attacking the Islamic State’s recruitment efforts on social media. [2] They are often associated with 4chan which could be good or bad depending on who you ask. Having followed them myself in the past, the goal is almost always some kind of justice, which it is in this case as well; they want to bring the incident to light and make sure the perpetrators cannot hide or be covered for. This is important to understand before any ethical analysis is started so we can have an idea of what their goals and intentions are. A short summary of this case is that in 2012 two members of the Steubenville High School football team sexually assaulted an underage girl who was passed out and spread it around on group chats/social media. At some point Anonymous found out and decided that it had been long enough without any action against the people involved and took it into their own hands and began spreading it around twitter, holding rallies in the town, and bringing it to the attention of news organizations across the country and world leading to a media field day over the town that went on for months. It brought a lot of negative attention to the town which many residents did not like. [1] Now that the history and the players is out there, the ethical analysis can begin. First Utilitarian Ethics will be used. Utilitarian Ethics is in the simplest terms, that “the morally right action is the action that produces the most good.” [3] In other words, it could be taken as meaning the ends justify the means; the consequences are what matters. Looking at Steubenville, let us first list out the main consequences: it brought negative attention to the town and could be harmful to the businesses and reputations of people who lived there causing them to speak out against the attention, some of the people involved were receiving threats, it gave courage to many other women to come out about their experience and brought it to the forefront of the national discourse, and it brought attention to something that would have likely been swept under the rug. While there are some clear negative consequences, they are fairly minor in the grand scheme of things and led to some people appearing to defend sexual assault. The positives of women being able to speak out against sexual assault and rape far outweigh the negatives of receiving bad press due to it, it brought an issue forward that has been affecting women for decades, if not centuries. Small town coverups have been happening for so long and people had kind of just taken an out of sight out of mind approach to it. By bringing it to the forefront it has allowed and will continue to allow women to get justice, tell their story, and find some sense of comfort or closure. For this reason, it benefitted society at large much more than it hurt it and is therefore morally correct under Utilitarianism. Moving on to Deontological Ethics we will find a similar answer, but first a quick review of Deontology. Deontological Ethics examines the action more than the consequences of the action, judging it based on the morality of the choices given. The choices are judged against certain moral standards, sometimes referred to as maxims, and depending on what is being violated it does not matter how good the outcome is. [4] A few base rules for this situation include do not lie, do not cause harm, and do not sexually assault. One could argue that by bringing attention to the situation it caused harm to the innocent people in the town, however in my experience, people in small towns often have some idea of what is going on even if they do not know for sure and are therefore causing harm to the victims by keeping quiet. Furthermore, by keeping it quiet and hoping it goes away those involved are essentially lying about doing anything about it. These coupled with the fact that the crime itself was sexual assault mean that Anonymous was correct to expose the issue to the world. The perpetrators got a slap on the wrist with only a couple years of detention even with the media outrage. [1] Without the media outrage, it would likely have been even less if anything at all. This is why it was the morally correct thing to do under Deontological Ethics. This has shown how Anonymous’s actions were morally correct under both Utilitarianism and Deontology. Both consequences and the choice to take the action were both morally correct. Had nothing been done, it would have simply been forgotten to time as another victim staying quiet out of fear or being ignored like many of the women who came out about their experiences after news broke. [1] While hacktivism can often be a contentious issue morally and ethically speaking, I think in this case it was warranted and clear cut for the most part. Some businesses or people may have suffered in the short-term due to the attention, but it means in the long-term women will be less afraid to come out about their experiences.

Injustice in America has been and will be an issue for years to come. Every year millions of Americans either have their cases unheard, dismissed, or even silenced. In the small city of Steubenville, Ohio, a High School girl had her most intimate boundaries violated and was made a mockery of among locals to the area. The girl, who was not named, was taken advantage of at a High School party in late 2012. Avoiding the despicable details of what occurred, the timeline of the crime lasted a few hours, all of the acts being well-documented on social media and shared with other students of her year. The case was originally kept between local authorities, the girl and the perpetrators involved. It is debatable if without the intervention of Internet “hacktivist” group, Anonymous, that she would receive the justice she truly deserved. The city of Steubenville suffers the consequences of these young men to this day and has had its reputation dragged through the mud due to these events. This case invites discussion about whether or not it was appropriate for the outside illegal intervention of Anonymous and if the shame brought to this city was justified. As many situations go in life, there is no black and white answer and both sides need to seriously reconsider their course of action in regards to this case. In order to decide whether or not it was appropriate for Anonymous to take the actions they did, we must look into the circumstances of the crime and how it was originally handled. The crime occurred in the early hours of August 11th, 2012. After the victim woke up dazed and with her clothes missing she reported the crime to local law enforcement. Nearly a year later the boys responsible were convicted and charged with rape of a minor. Although justice was served in the judicial sense, Anonymous witnessed the way the case was covered. The sympathy shown for the boys responsible and the absence of sympathy for the victim. This greatly displeased certain members and they decided to get involved. It was not the first time Anonymous has made an issue their own. As their group is considered to be decentralized, which means the political agenda of one member may not align with another. Every member is considered an independent entity and will take on their own “projects”. A group of members eventually released leaked documents from the investigations, most importantly, a disturbing video of a bystander recording the aftermath of the crime making crude remarks such as “... they raped her quicker than Mike Tyson raped that one girl.” The general public after seeing such distasteful commentary in regard to a rape victim became enraged and took to the streets and social media to display their discontent. Protest demonstrations popped up in Steubenville, creating a lot of disruption for residents there. Although the actions of a few young men should not dictate the image of the entire population, it is very callous of the town to wish the case was kept low profile or that it’s only the responsibility of law enforcement to deliver justice. The way media outlets portrayed the young convicts as unfortunate souls who were misguided instead of selfish criminals who not only took advantage of an unfortunate situation but shamed and humiliated the victim for the eyes of her peers was very callous. I believe it was very selfish of the town to focus on their self image versus the atrocious crime their environment bred and hosted. Furthering the points from above, it is indeed debatable if without Anonymous’ intervention this girl would have gotten the justice she deserves. Justice is not only in terms of criminal prosecution, there are other aspects of justice as well. The social implications of being a criminal being one of the most important. The negative connotation associated with sex offenders/felons is ideally a huge deterrent for such behavior. Criminals will always exist and although this method isn’t foolproof, it stops a lot otherwise “normal” people from committing heinous crimes. In my belief, if these young men were lucid enough to play the victim and know the consequences of their actions well enough to state their lives were ruined from this incident that they should be punished with the fullest extent of the law. There is no use in treating these men any different than any other rapist just because they happened to be 16 years old when this event occurred. Taking advantage of an unconscious girl and degrading her on social media is not a silly mistake. It is a calculated and horrendous act against another human being that should be punished accordingly. It is not fair that these men were painted as the victim by certain media outlets, they deserve little to no sympathy. These men are only sorry because they got caught. Like everyone else who rightfully convicted of a sex crime, they should be shamed and ousted for their crimes. It is so important that crimes like this are not treated as mistakes, you cannot mistakenly abuse another human being in a vulnerable position and post it for everyone to see on social media. Anonymous did the right thing in bringing attention to these two young men, but the wrong thing in blaming the entire city for what has occurred. The actions of a group of young men and the law enforcement involved do not accurately reflect the character of every individual in the city. It is unfortunate the city will forever live in infamy for the actions of these young men, but in hindsight they aren’t in a unique situation. Plenty of “small towns” across America and even across the globe are plagued by what has happened in their past. It is part of the human existence that brings awful people and awful actions. History should not be erased in fear that other people will make the same mistakes. It is the duty of the city to not hide their past, and also the duty of Americans to uphold the level of contempt we have towards criminals like ​Ma'lik Richmond and Trent Mays. Their names deserve the level of disgust they carry and Anonymous helped the community get there. Returning to the point above, Anonymous’ intervention with this case did not follow the law. Hacktivism always comes at the expense of the law, in this situation it is fair to make the argument the ends did justify the means. Without the leaks of the evidence in this case, it is reasonable to assume this case after being tried would have been swept under the rug and the men involved would have gotten to live a life essentially free of the consequences of their actions. As rape victims live in permanent peril and trauma from what happens to them, the offenders deserve to live with the permanent consequences and guilt for their actions. It does not matter how “young” the offenders are. 16 year olds do not share the same cognitive ability as children, they need to be held accountable for their actions and labelled for what they are. It is not a silly mistake to rape someone, and the consequences of their actions deserve to be echoed forever.

In life, we face many scenarios in which we must make crucial decisions to decide to what is right and what is wrong? What is moral and what is legal? In order to make sure that everyone’s right is safe and secure in society we must answer some ethical questions before making decisions and passing laws that guarantee those rights. Ethics is a very important concept to study and it plays an influential role in many ways, in helping us manage our social and personal life issues, in influencing government policy and in helping us understand the purpose of life. It helps us to stand up for what is right and rejecting things that needs to be considered immoral in our societies and cultures. In situations in which we need to consider what is right and what is wrong we must weigh in the possibilities of understanding the advantages and disadvantages of our decision. We must be aware of the negative and positive consequences of our decision and then henceforth come up with the decision that has long -positive benefits for the whole society . Sometimes to correct any wrong in society we must take the illegal steps to correct them. An example of a situation could like this could be described by an incident that happened in a town of Steubenville Ohio , known for high school sports and the birthplace of Dean Martin(phillips). A teen assault was committed by some members of a football team and an Anonymous group decided to intervene(phillips) . They published some videos on social media and that sparked outrage in the community(phillips). This divided and led an uproar in the community , however, it gave generations of women to speak up against abuse(phillips). This incident is a good example and it helps us to think what is ethical, legal, illegal , moral and immoral so we can make a decision that seems ethical in nature and is beneficial for the whole society and communities in future. Considering this situation we need to first consider what hacking really is and what type of it is legal or illegal. According to the economic times hacking is an unauthorized access to a computer’s security system(Bridewell). It is an attempt to gain access to someone’s else private information online(BrideWell). There are different types of hacking, including hacking for fun, hacking for political purposes, hacking as a part of organized crime, hacking for notoriety(Bridewell). Hacking for fun is passion as well as a job. It was viewed as an offence under the Computer Misuse Act of 1990(Bridewell). Hacking for political purposes is when a party uses personal accounts, websites, and emails of other parties(Bridewell). Hacking for organized crime is when hacking is a big business and is very sophisticated in nature(Bridewell). Hacking for notoriety is when younger generation hacks someone’s account to prove other about their knowledge about computer systems. (Bridewell) Therefore, to consider whether hacking is legal or illegal we must understand what the law says about it. In the United States for example different states have different policies regarding hacking. For example, in the state of California the penalty for hacking is based on the severity of the crime.
